<p class="p1"><br></p>
<p class="p1" data-pasted="true"><strong>Linking Asset Data to Operational Needs</strong></p>
<p>Next, defining what data is required for each asset, it’s important to step back and consider: <strong>“What decisions or actions will this information support?”</strong></p>
<p>Each data point should serve a meaningful purpose helping teams maintain, operate, or manage assets more effectively. By focusing only on information that supports real-world needs, we avoid unnecessary complexity and ensure the data we request is both relevant and valuable.</p>
<p>This section helps connect asset data to practical applications — such as planned maintenance, compliance, or energy tracking — ensuring that every requirement has a clear rationale. When we can confidently say, <strong>“We need this data because it enables this,”</strong></p>
<p>Below are typical operational needs that commonly drive the requirement for structured asset data:</p>
<table data-pasted="true" style="width: 100%; height: 188px;">
<thead><tr>
<th style="background-color: rgb(14, 30, 61);"><p class="p1"><strong><span style="color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">Asset Type</span></strong></p></th>
<th style="background-color: rgb(14, 30, 61);"><p class="p1"><strong><span style="color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">Use Case</span></strong></p></th>
<th style="background-color: rgb(14, 30, 61);"><p class="p1"><strong><span style="color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">Why the Data is Needed</span></strong></p></th>
</tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><p class="p1">Fire Alarm Panel</p></td>
<td><p class="p1">Compliance, Maintenance</p></td>
<td><p class="p1">Required for fire safety certification and PPM setup</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><p class="p1">Chiller Unit</p></td>
<td><p class="p1">Energy Tracking, Lifecycle Planning</p></td>
<td><p class="p1">Needed to monitor energy use and plan for replacement</p></td>
